Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

The data set I have chosen to analyze is the tmdb movies data set which contains information about various movies stored in the movie database (TMDb). This data set contains data on over 10,000 movies including the user ratings, year and date of release, name of director, cast, runtime, budget and revenue generated from the movies.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

In this analysis, I will be focusing on the features that impact profitability and revenue of movie productions as well as their profit margins in general. My analysis will try to answer the following questions:

  • Which movies were the most and least profitable movies
  • Which are the top 10 production companies who generated the most profit
  • Who are the top 10 movie Directors who generated the most profit and revenue
  • Top 10 Movie Genres that generated the most profit and revenue
  • Does higher budgets result in higher revenue?
  • Does higher or increased revenue guarantee profits?
  • Will higher budgets result in profit generation?
  • Are movies with higher popularity ratings guaranteed to make profits?
  • Does the popularity rating of a movie impact the revenue generation?
  • Do all movie productions generate revenue?
  • Does revenue generation from movie production guarantee profits?

#Create a new function to automate the generation of the movies with the highest and lowest profit.

def profit_maxmin(p):
    #use the 'idmax' and 'idmin' functions to find the index of highest and lowest profit movies.
    max_index = movies_df[p].idxmax()
    low_index = movies_df[p].idxmin()
    max_profit = pd.DataFrame(movies_df.loc[max_index,:])
    low_profit = pd.DataFrame(movies_df.loc[low_index,:])
    mov_profit = pd.concat([max_profit,low_profit],axis = 1)
    
    #print the details of the movies having the highest and lowest profits
    print("The movie with the highest profit is " + " = ", movies_df['original_title'][max_index], "with a profit of $",  movies_df['profit'].max())
    print("The movie with the least profit is " + "  = ", movies_df['original_title'][low_index], "with a profit of $",  movies_df['profit'].min())
    
    return mov_profit

Conclusions¶

  • The highest grossing movie in terms or profit is 'Avatar' while 'The warriors way' made the highest loss of all movies analyzed.
  • Paramount pictures is the highest grossing movie production company for profits made.
  • The Director with the highest Profits generated from movies directed is Steven Spielberg.
  • The movies genre with the highest profit as well as revenue generation is the 'Comedy' genre.
  • Higher budget does not guarantee increased revenue or profit.
  • Higher revenue will result in higher profits based on their strong correlation.
  • The movie popularity could affect the revenue and profits generated.
  • Only 52% of the movies analysed generated revenues after production while a high 42% did not generate any revenue.
  • Even though 52% generated revenues, only 41% of the movies made actual profit which indicates that 11% of the movies that generated revenue failed to make profit. This data shows that less than 50% of the movie productions resulted in profitable ventures.

Limitations¶

  • The dataset had a lot of missing and null values which resulted in the affected rows being deleted.
  • The revenue and budget amounts did not have currency units to enable us ascertain the uniformity of the figures presented. I have adopted the USD(dollar) currency for this analysis.
  • The dataset contains details of movies produced between 1960 and 2015 which might not be enough to make assumptions for the movie industry statistics of today.
